02:59.920 --> 03:02.280
You also have to get through the train and everything.

03:02.280 --> 03:10.440
So an open transport expands the domain, and also, topic-wise, the main topic today is

03:10.440 --> 03:14.720
open source software, but of course also open data, open APIs.

03:14.720 --> 03:17.320
They are very important in this space as well.

03:17.320 --> 03:22.480
So this all comes together in a bigger picture.

03:22.480 --> 03:25.020
We do want to talk about more than just railways.

03:25.020 --> 03:30.100
We also want to cover public transport basically, but want to be open, because in the end it's

03:30.100 --> 03:35.680
about the future of mobility, how do we move around, and how do we do that in a way which

03:35.680 --> 03:38.240
doesn't destroy the planet.

03:38.240 --> 03:43.080
So I think that's one of the underlying motivations for many of us.

03:43.080 --> 03:45.000
It's about sustainable transport.

03:45.000 --> 03:50.740
It's about creating the means of transportation, which will serve us for the next decades and

03:50.740 --> 03:52.160
millennia and whatever.

03:52.160 --> 03:54.760
Yeah, and we can't do that alone, of course.

03:54.760 --> 03:59.760
That's why we do it together, and we want to create things together.

03:59.760 --> 04:01.520
That's why we built the Open Rail Foundation.

04:01.520 --> 04:04.280
